\pard\keepn\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\b\fs36 Critique of the film \i Proof\i0\par
\pard\b0\fs24 By {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:jmdk@smac.ulaval.ca"}}{\fldrslt{\ul Jean-Marie De Koninck}}}\ulnone\f1\fs24\par
After the death of her father, a brilliant mathematician (Anthony Hopkins), Catherine (Gwyneth Paltrow), herself also a mathematician, contemplates interrupting her studies. In that period of self-doubt and calling into question, reflections about gift, heredity, the passion for maths and the folly of the human genius blend with the existential reflections of a young woman confused about her future.\par
Notwithstanding the clumsy translation of the English title \i Proof\i0  into the French \i Preuve irr\'e9futable\i0  (a shameful tautology, a proof is by definition irrefutable!), this film offers a blends of a romantic intrigue with an often challenging father-daughter relationship.\par
Moreover, the direction is so good, the dynamic of the scenes so enduring, that one barely realizes that the plot revolves essentially around a single setting and only four characters, three of which being mathematicians. \par
The mathematical field to which the notorious \i proof\i0   applies is never explicitly mentioned. However, since allusions are made to prime numbers, random matrices, the limit inferior of a series, and to the fact that many mathematicians have tackled it since the dawn of time, specialists agree to say that this film deals with the prime twins conjecture, the claim that there are infinitely many prime numbers p such that p + 2 is also prime.\par
This film is definitely worth watching. It depicts the universe of mathematicians in an accurate way and makes claims that are irrefutable and others that are not...\cf4\par
